# Promise real api Timeout Behavior — Quick Notes

## The Core Fact
A Promise has **no built-in timeout**. It doesn't know or care how long it's taking.

- If nothing ever calls `resolve()` or `reject()`, the Promise stays **pending forever**.
- This is true at 10 minutes, 10 hours, or 10 days — no automatic change of state.
- A Promise does **NOT**:
  - auto-resolve
  - auto-reject
  - auto-error
  ...just because time passed. Time alone never settles a Promise.

## What Actually Settles It (in the real world)

| Client / Layer | Default timeout? | What happens if it hangs |
|---|---|---|
| `fetch()` | None | Stays pending until OS/network layer or server closes the connection → then rejects (`Failed to fetch`) |
| `axios` | None (opt-in via `timeout` config) | Hangs indefinitely unless you set one |
| `XMLHttpRequest` | None (opt-in via `.timeout` property) | Same — waits forever unless configured |
| Node.js `http`/`https` | Socket-level timeout exists, but not request-level by default | Eventually `ETIMEDOUT`/`ECONNRESET` once socket gives up |
| Real servers / load balancers (nginx, AWS ALB, etc.) | Usually YES (commonly 30–60s) | Server/proxy kills the connection → client-side promise then rejects |

## Bottom Line

| Question | Answer |
|---|---|
| Does it auto-resolve? | No |
| Does it auto-reject? | No, by itself |
| Does it error out? | Only if something external (server/network/proxy) kills the connection ie reject state|
| State at 10 min if nothing intervenes? | **Still pending** |

## The Fix — Always Set Your Own Timeout

Never rely on "it'll eventually time out on its own." Build the timeout explicitly.

**Using `Promise.race()`:**
```javascript
function apiCallWithTimeout(apiPromise, timeoutMs) {
  const timeout = new Promise((_, reject) =>
    setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`Timed out after ${timeoutMs}ms`)), timeoutMs)
  );
  return Promise.race([apiPromise, timeout]);
}
```

**Using `AbortController` (for `fetch` — also cancels the real request):**
```javascript
const controller = new AbortController();
const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 5000);

fetch(url, { signal: controller.signal })
  .then(res => res.json())
  .catch(err => {
    if (err.name === "AbortError") console.log("Request timed out");
  })
  .finally(() => clearTimeout(timeoutId));
```

> **Note:** `Promise.race()` doesn't cancel the losing promise — the original slow request keeps running in the background even after timeout wins. `AbortController` is the only way to actually cancel the underlying work.
